{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15007"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15007"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.15,0.41,0.08,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66747"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7695"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52201"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5261"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18807"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the pharmacological properties of penicillins is essential for their appropriate clinical use.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the distribution of penicillins in the body?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Concentrates mainly in adipose tissue","Distributes primarily in intracellular fluid","Distributes primarily in extracellular fluid","Concentrates exclusively in plasma","Distributes equally between intracellular and extracellular fluid"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPenicillins \u003Cstrong\u003Edistribute primarily in extracellular fluid\u003C/strong\u003E and can penetrate most body tissues. This distribution pattern is important for their effectiveness against extracellular bacterial pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentrates mainly in adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - Penicillins are hydrophilic molecules and do not preferentially distribute in fat\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistributes primarily in intracellular fluid\u003C/strong\u003E - Penicillins have poor penetration into cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentrates exclusively in plasma\u003C/strong\u003E - While penicillins are found in plasma, they distribute throughout extracellular fluid\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistributes equally between intracellular and extracellular fluid\u003C/strong\u003E - The hydrophilic nature of penicillins limits their intracellular penetration\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis distribution pattern aligns with penicillins\u0027 mechanism of action, as they need to reach the cell wall of bacteria, which is accessible in the extracellular space.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Penicillin V is more stable in gastric acid than penicillin G, making it suitable for oral administration","Oral penicillins typically reach peak serum levels in 60-90 minutes after ingestion","Penicillins distribute primarily in extracellular fluid and penetrate most body tissues","Penicillin G and V have similar antimicrobial spectra focused on gram-positive organisms"],"references":["Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 A